content.description: There is one mixed route around right on the east side of the wall, near the center of the face. Follow the bolts, then past a couple cracks to bolts and anchor.
content.location: Around the right side of the wall, east-facing.

climbs.name: Snatcher
climbs.fa: Sean Woods, Ron Cotman, Viktor Kramer, 2009

content.description: Head up following bolts past a 'mini-roof' and an angled crack.
content.location: 2nd route right of the baby pine, also 2nd left from right end of south face. There is a bit of an angled rail protruding from the face near the start (see photo).

climbs.name: Snapper
climbs.fa: Ron Cotman, Sean Woods, Viktor Kramar; 2012

content.description: Fun slabby route the heads up and under a mini-roof feature. Well protected, but you might want a BD #0.4 if you're on the shorter side of things for the upper-middle part of the route. If you're 5'10", don't bother.
content.protection: 5 bolts and it's own chain anchor
content.location: Middle of Central Park wall; look for a mini-roof feature just left of the thin undercling flake that constitutes the crux of neighboring "Snatcher" (also 5.9+).

content.description: Route just right of the pine, follow discontinuous cracks up wall to finish on easier cracks.
content.location: Just right of the large pine.

content.description: Just left of the large pine tree, follow bolts up the slab past the numerous white patches (looks like flakes broke off).
content.location: Second route from left end of wall, just left of the huge pine.

climbs.name: Fifth Avenue
climbs.fa: Ron Cotman, Gordon Briody, Viktor Kramar, 2009

content.description: Follow bolts up slab to a big flake. Move around the left side of it and continue up to top.
content.location: Furthest right on south-facing wall, look for the big flake.

content.description: Head up past a bolt just before a crack, then continue up past the various cracks to the top past one last high bolt.
content.location: Just left of a small baby pine tree.

content.description: Far left side of wall, follow varying-sized curvy cracks to a bolt, continue to anchors.
content.location: If using the low-angle chute to access the wall, this will be the first climb you reach. Left of the big pine tree on the ledge.
